Content:
The inner platform arises out of how the JQuery ($) function/object and all the methods behave.<p>Compare conventional DOM code:<p><pre><code>    var d = document.getElementById('elm');
    d.style.color = 'red';
    d.onclick = function() {}
</code></pre>
To JQuery code:<p><pre><code>    $('#elm').color('red').click(function(){});
</code></pre>
Now what if you want to add debug statements between the style and event statements?  Using JQuery you have to "undo" the inner platform in order to get access to the actual element object:<p><pre><code>    var d = $('#elm').get(0);
    // debug code
    $(d).color('red')
    // debug code
    $(d).click(function(){});
</code></pre>
All of a sudden what made JQuery concise starts getting in the way.
